 Italy -- tFacing Plurality (from Marginality): The German-Jewish Reception of William James -- tLeo Strauss on Lessing’s Spinozism -- tStrauss, Schmitt, and Peterson, or: Comparative Contours of the “Theological-Political Predicament” -- t“Let me tell you a story”: Walter Benjamin and the History of the Future -- tJacob Taubes, Karl Löwith, and the Interpretation of Jewish History -- tThe Jews They Were and the Philosophers They Wished to Become -- tNo “Love of the Jewish People”? Robert Weltsch’s and Hans Jonas’s Correspondence with Hannah Arendt on Eichmann in Jerusalem -- tBibliography Paul Mendes-Flohr -- tList of Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the Enlightenment period, German-Jewish intellectuals have been prominent voices in the multi-facetted discourse on the reinterpretation of Jewish tradition in light of modern thinking. Paul Mendes-Flohr, one of the towering figures of current scholarship on German-Jewish intellectual history, has made invaluable contributions to a better understanding of the religious, cultural and political dimensions of these thinkers’ encounter with German and European culture, including the tension between their loyalty to Judaism and the often competing claims of non-Jewish society and culture. This volume assembles essays by internationally acknowledged scholars in the field who intend to honor Mendes-Flohr’s work by portraying the abundance of religious, philosophical, aesthetical and political aspects dominating the thinking of those famous thinkers populating German Jewry's rich and complex intellectual world in the modern period. It also provides a fresh theoretical outlook on trends in Jewish intellectual history, raising new questions concerning the dialectics of assimilation. In addition to that, the volume sheds light on thinkers and debates that hitherto have not been accorded full scholarly attention.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aJewish philosophyzGermany. 0aJudaism and philosophy. 0aJudaismzGermanyxHistory. 4aDeutsch-Jüdische Geschichte. 4aJüdische Geistesgeschichte. 4aJüdische Philosophie. 4aModernes Judentum. 4aReligionsphilosphie. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh  aGerman-Jewish History.  aJewish Intellectual History.  aJewish Philosophy.  aModern Judaism.  aReligious Philosophy.1 aBatnitzky, Leora F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiemann, Asher D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraiterman, Zachary J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFisher, Cass, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoetschel, Willi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGordon, Peter E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGottlieb, Michah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHollander, Dana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKajon, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKavka, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKepnes, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLazier, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMagid, Shaul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeyer, Michael A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPollock, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUrban, Martina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUrban, Martina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.lo